<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-905-546  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 905 546.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Dec 1989 v14 n13 p248(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Images. (computer image processing)(includes related article onhardware and software solutions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Penney, Walt.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computerized image-processing takes gray-scale and color-imagedata of real-word phenomena as input and performs statisticalanalysis or enhancements, generating digitized images as output.andO;Digital images usually require many megabytes of storage andhigh-bandwidth pathways for acceptable performance.andP;  'Point'image-processing functions operate on individual pixels;'neighborhood' operators work on groups of pixels.andP;  Input sourcesinclude satellite data, optical scanners and video digitization.andO;Images reside in a frame buffer for processing, and the output maybe the image data itself (as a display), or a hard copy.andP;  Atypical imaging system includes a frame buffer, display monitor,video digitizer, video source and accelerator.andP;  Medical scans,earth-science data processing, and document management areimportant image-processing applications.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Image processingNew TechniqueCost ReductionPerformance ImprovementWorkstations.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Typical image-processing workstation. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>